## Important Guidelines

1. **Game System:** All exercises use existing BallCODE game system. No new mini-games need to be built.
2. **Picture Book Format:** Each spread = story panel + visual + QR/short URL to game exercise.
3. **Age Group:** Grades 3–8 (Elementary & Middle school). Keep language accessible, concepts concrete.
4. **Story-First:** 70% story, 30% skill inserts. Maximize engagement while ensuring learning.
5. **CTAs:** Only in Skill Pit‑Stop and end-of-chapter. Never interrupt story flow.
6. **Partner Ready:** Structure supports white-label branding (IBM Watson, Cisco, etc.). Fully working integration is the unique selling point.
7. **Notion Integration:** All production tracking happens in Notion database with progress formulas and checklists. Structure supports commenting and checkboxes for collaboration.
8. **Workflow:** Kids read the story, then do exercises in the game. The book and game work together seamlessly.

## When Writing Content

- Keep stories engaging and adventure-focused
- Make coding/math concepts concrete through basketball analogies
- Use character names consistently (Nova, Atlas, Pixel, Anchor, Coach Circuit, Arc/Watson)
- Include reflection questions: "What changed your decision and why?"
- Ensure exercises map directly to existing BallCODE game mechanics
- Write for grades 3–8: accessible language, concrete examples, visual thinking

## When Creating Assets

- Play diagrams: basketball court with player movements
- Code/pseudocode diagrams: visual representation of coding concept
- Character/monster art: consistent with world bible
- QR codes: link to specific Try‑It drill in game
- Glif prompts: detailed enough to generate appropriate visuals

